workflow.name: Comprehensive contact enrichment with Apollo, LinkedIn, and GPT-4o for HubSpot
workflow.description:
### Summary
Turns a plain name + email into a fully-enriched HubSpot contact by matching the person in Apollo, pulling their latest LinkedIn activity, summarising the findings with GPT-4o, and upserting the clean data into HubSpot

### Key use-cases
SDRs enriching inbound demo requests before routing

RevOps teams keeping executive records fresh

Marketers building highly-segmented email audiences

### Inputs
|Field	|Type|	Example|
|-|-|-|
name	|string|	‚ÄúJane Doe‚Äù
email|	string	|‚Äújane@acme.com‚Äù

### Required credentials
|Service	|Node	|Notes|
|-|-|-|
Apollo.io API key |	HTTP Request ‚Äì ‚ÄúEnrich with Apollo‚Äù	|Set in header x-api-key
RapidAPI key| (Fresh-LinkedIn-Profile-Data)	‚ÄúGet recent posts‚Äù|	Header x-rapidapi-key
OpenAI	3 LangChain nodes|	Supply an API key| default model gpt-4o-mini
HubSpot OAuth2|	‚ÄúEnrich in HubSpot‚Äù|	Add/create any custom contact properties referenced

High-level flow
Trigger ‚Äì Runs when another workflow passes name & email.

Clean ‚Äì JS Code node normalises & deduplicates emails.

Apollo match ‚Äì Queries /people/match; skips if no person.

LinkedIn fetch ‚Äì Grabs up to 3 original posts from last 30 days.

AI summary chain

OpenAI ‚Üí Structured/Auto-fixing parsers

Produces a strict JSON block with job title, location, summaries, etc.

HubSpot upsert ‚Äì Maps every key (plus five custom properties) into the contact record.

Sticky-notes annotate the canvas; error-prone bits have retry logic.

messageValues.message:
=# Overview
You are ‚ÄúHubSpot-Enrichment-Agent‚Äù, a data-cleaning assistant that converts messy person JSON enrichment data into concise, human-friendly fields ready to upsert into HubSpot. 

## OBJECTIVE
Return **one** JSON object with exactly these keys:

{
  "email": string|null,
  "linkedin_url": string|null,
  "job_title": string|null, // title at the company that matches the email domain
  "city": string|null,
  "state": string|null,
  "country_region": string|null,
  "experience_summary": string|null, // 3-4 recent roles, bullet list, newest ‚Üí oldest
  "education_summary": string|null, // highest degree(s) & institution(s), 1-2 lines
  "recent_linkedin_activity": string|null
}

## RULES & LOGIC

1. **Email, LinkedIn URL, City, Country/Region**  
   *Pass through directly if present; else `null`.*

2. **Job Title (relevant)**  
   - Use the employment record whose `organization_name` (or website) shares the **same email domain** as `email`.  
   - If no domain match, pick the most recent item where `current == true`.  
   - Strip membership-only titles (‚ÄúMember‚Äù, ‚ÄúAngel Investor‚Äù) unless no better option exists.

3. **Experience Summary**  
   - Sort `employment_history` by `start_date` DESC.  
   - Select the first **3‚Äì4** roles that are either `current == true` _or_ have an `end_date` within the last 10 years.  
   - Format each as:  
     `‚Ä¢ <Title>, <Org> ‚Äî <YYYY-start> ‚Üí <"Present" | YYYY-end>`  
   - Join with line breaks.  Return `null` if list is empty.

4. **Education Summary**  
   - Look for the highest‚Äêlevel degree (Doctorate > MBA/Master‚Äôs > Bachelor‚Äôs > Associate > Other).  
   - Summarise as:  
     `<Degree>, <Institution> (<YYYY-end>)`.  
   - If multiple relevant degrees, include up to two lines.  
   - If no education data, return `null`.

5. **Recent LinkedIn Activity**  
   - If a `recent_activity` or similar field exists, pull the latest **1-3** public posts or updates.  
   - Summarise in plain text, e.g.,  
     `‚ÄúCommented on procurement AI article‚Äù (3 days ago)`  
   - If no activity data, set to `null`. Do NOT make up activity.

6. **Null handling**  
   - Any missing or empty field **must** be literal `null` (not empty string).

7. **Output style**  
   - Pure JSON, no markdown.  
   - No additional keys, comments, or nested objects.

## Grammar and Punctuation
  - ensure that your output is cleanly formatted for readiness to import into CRM, including removing uneceesary spaces or other symbols and capitalizing names. (e.g., "sales director" should become "Sales Director")

Return only that final JSON. Example output:
{
  "email": "dustin.c@gatekeeperhq.com",
  "linkedin_url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/dustinclinard",
  "job_title": "Chief Revenue Officer (CRO)",
  "city": "Concord",
  "country_region": "United States",
  "experience_summary": "‚Ä¢ Chief Revenue Officer, Gatekeeper ‚Äî 2024 ‚Üí Present\n‚Ä¢ Founding Member, Revenue Collective ‚Äî 2019 ‚Üí Present\n‚Ä¢ Member, Partnership Leaders ‚Äî 2020 ‚Üí Present\n‚Ä¢ Founder & Growth Consultant, Sales Growth Musings ‚Äî 2016 ‚Üí Present",
  "education_summary": null,
  "recent_linkedin_activity": null
}

data.details:
The IF node can be used to implement binary conditional logic in your workflow. You can set up one-to-many conditions to evaluate each item of data being inputted into the node. That data will either evaluate to TRUE or FALSE and route out of the node accordingly.

This node has multiple types of conditions: Bool, String, Number, and Date & Time.

data.details: The Code node allows you to execute JavaScript in your workflow.

The Filter node can be used to filter items based on a condition. If the condition is met, the item will be passed on to the next node. If the condition is not met, the item will be omitted. Conditions can be combined together by AND(meet all conditions), or OR(meet at least one condition).
